Data Wrangling with dplyr

WCM Biostatistics Computing Club

Jan 1, 0001

Image courtesy of Allison Horst’s Twitter: @allison_horst

Introduction

Why dplyr?

  1. Efficiency*

  2. Simple syntax

  3. Function chaining

  4. Ability to analyze external databases

  5. Works well with other packages in tidyverse suite
    1. ggplot2
    2. tidyr
    3. stringr
    4. forcats
    5. purrr

*if you start dealing with data sets with > 1 million rows, data.table will be much faster

library(tidyverse)
## ── Attaching packages ────────────── tidyverse 1.2.1 ──
## ✔ ggplot2 3.2.1     ✔ purrr   0.3.2
## ✔ tibble  2.1.3     ✔ dplyr   0.8.3

data("iris")

Tibbles

  • Can think of tibbles as an “update” to the data.frame object class in R

  • Updates relevant for using dplyr:

    • Vectors of length 1 are automatically recycled

    • Newly created vectors can be referenced in the same line of code

  • Other perks: only the first 10 lines print to the screen so your console doesn’t get overloaded

  • Read more about tibbles here: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/tibbles.html

  • dplyr automatically converts objects to tbl_df (tibble data frame) objects

    • You can do this manually with tbl_df()
glimpse(iris)
## Observations: 150

Piping

  • %>% operator from library(magitrr)

  • Use %>% to send an object (typically a dataframe) to the next function

  • The function you pipe to will use the object in front of the %>% as its first argument

iris %>% head() # equivalent to head(iris)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
##          <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 2          4.9         3            1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa 
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2 setosa 
## 5          5           3.6          1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4 setosa
iris %>% head(n=3) # equivalent to head(iris, n=3)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
##          <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 2          4.9         3            1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa
  • If you don’t want it to be the first argument, use .
iris %>% lm(Sepal.Width ~ Sepal.Length, data=.)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Sepal.Width ~ Sepal.Length, data = .)
## 
## Coefficients:
##  (Intercept)  Sepal.Length  
##      3.41895      -0.06188

  • Shortcut for %>% is CTRL + SHIFT + M (or CMD + SHIFT + M for OSX)

  • A verb is a function that takes a data frame as the first argument, eg. head()

  • The entire tidyverse suite operates under this verb function structure, making piping especially convenient

Main verbs

arrange()

  • Sort data frame by column(s), lowest to highest
arrange(iris, Petal.Length) 
## # A tibble: 150 x 5
##    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
##           <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
##  1          4.6         3.6          1           0.2 setosa 
##  2          4.3         3            1.1         0.1 setosa 
##  3          5.8         4            1.2         0.2 setosa 
##  4          5           3.2          1.2         0.2 setosa 
##  5          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  6          5.4         3.9          1.3         0.4 setosa 
##  7          5.5         3.5          1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  8          4.4         3            1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  9          5           3.5          1.3         0.3 setosa 
## 10          4.5         2.3          1.3         0.3 setosa 
## # … with 140 more rows

  • If you specify a variable of class factor or character, you will rearrange the rows to alphabetical order

  • Use desc() if you want the opposite order

arrange(iris, desc(Species), # sort z to a since species is a factor
        Sepal.Width)

filter()

  • Return rows matching specified conditions

  • Use with >, >=, <, <=, |, !, %in%, ==, and !=. Separating conditions by , represents the & argument.

summarise()

  • Condenses data down to one value per group
summarise(iris, mean(Petal.Length))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `mean(Petal.Length)`
##                  <dbl>
## 1                 3.76
summarise(iris, sd_pl = sd(Petal.Length), var_pl = sd(Petal.Length)^2)
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   sd_pl var_pl
##   <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  1.77   3.12

group_by()

  • Invisibly groups data by specified column(s)

  • Use with other verbs to get grouped information

iris %>% group_by(Species) 
## # A tibble: 150 x 5
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
##           <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
##  1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2 setosa 
##  2          4.9         3            1.4         0.2 setosa 
##  3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2 setosa 
##  5          5           3.6          1.4         0.2 setosa 
##  6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4 setosa 
##  7          4.6         3.4          1.4         0.3 setosa 
##  8          5           3.4          1.5         0.2 setosa 
##  9          4.4         2.9          1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 10          4.9         3.1          1.5         0.1 setosa 
## # … with 140 more rows
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarise(mean(Petal.Length), sd(Petal.Length)) %>%
  head()
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   Species    `mean(Petal.Length)` `sd(Petal.Length)`
##   <fct>                     <dbl>              <dbl>
## 1 setosa                     1.46              0.174
## 2 versicolor                 4.26              0.470
## 3 virginica                  5.55              0.552
  • Data will remain grouped until you use ungroup()

rename()

  • Give your columns new names. Syntax is newColumn = oldColumn.
iris %>% rename(sep_len = Sepal.Length) 
## # A tibble: 150 x 5
##    sep_len Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species

##  3     4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  4     4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2 setosa 
##  5     5           3.6          1.4         0.2 setosa 
##  6     5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4 setosa

##  8     5           3.4          1.5         0.2 setosa 
##  9     4.4         2.9          1.4         0.2 setosa 
## 10     4.9         3.1          1.5         0.1 setosa

  • If you have weird characters in your column names, put ` signs around the old column name, not "

Helper functions

row_number()

  • Specify which row number you want for your verb
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  filter(row_number() == 1)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species   
##          <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>     
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2 setosa    
## 2          7           3.2          4.7         1.4 versicolor
## 3          6.3         3.3          6           2.5 virginica
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  filter(row_number() == n())
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species   
##          <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>     
## 1          5           3.3          1.4         0.2 setosa    
## 2          5.7         2.8          4.1         1.3 versicolor
## 3          5.9         3            5.1         1.8 virginica

Fancy verbs

  • Scoped verbs end in _at(), _if() and _all() signifying the function should be applied too all variables, only at certain variables, or only if variables meet a certain condition.

  • ie. mutate_at(), mutate_if(), mutate_all(), summarise_if(), summarise_at(), summarise_all(), select_if(), select_at(), rename_if(), filter_all(), arrange_all(), group_by_at() …the list goes on!

  • Take the additional arguments .predicate, .funs, and .vars

  • A few examples (we will see more later)

iris %>% select_if(.predicate = is.numeric)
## # A tibble: 150 x 4
##    Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
##           <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl>
##  1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2
##  2          4.9         3            1.4         0.2
##  3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2
##  4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2
##  5          5           3.6          1.4         0.2
##  6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4
##  7          4.6         3.4          1.4         0.3
##  8          5           3.4          1.5         0.2
##  9          4.4         2.9          1.4         0.2
## 10          4.9         3.1          1.5         0.1
## # … with 140 more rows
iris %>% select_if(.predicate = is.numeric, .funs=funs(paste0("num_",.))) # can also be used to rename
## # A tibble: 150 x 4

  • I have never used any of the 'group_by_*()' but I imagine they’re useful when you have a large selection of identifiers/grouping variables that you can call easily with a predicate (for example, 'is.factor') or a .vars argument (such as '')

Miscellaneous verbs

lag()

  • Makes a new column with the value of one row previously

lead()

  • Makes a new column with the value of one row ahead
x <- runif(5)
cbind(ahead = lead(x), x, behind = lag(x))
##          ahead         x    behind
## [1,] 0.3370735 0.6534913        NA
## [2,] 0.7941706 0.3370735 0.6534913
## [3,] 0.7436784 0.7941706 0.3370735
## [4,] 0.5702559 0.7436784 0.7941706
## [5,]        NA 0.5702559 0.7436784
  • Can choose a time column to order your new values by, but be careful
df <- data.frame(year = 2000:2005, value = (0:5) ^ 2)
df
##   year value
## 1 2000     0
## 2 2001     1
## 3 2002     4
## 4 2003     9
## 5 2004    16
## 6 2005    25
scrambled <- df[sample(nrow(df)), ]
scrambled
##   year value
## 6 2005    25
## 3 2002     4
## 1 2000     0
## 4 2003     9
## 2 2001     1
## 5 2004    16
right <- mutate(scrambled, prev = lag(value, order_by = year))
arrange(right, year)
##   year value prev
## 1 2000     0   NA
## 2 2001     1    0
## 3 2002     4    1
## 4 2003     9    4
## 5 2004    16    9
## 6 2005    25   16
  • Lag and lead are very useful for longitudinal models

Joining functions

a <- data.frame(x1 = c("A","B","C"), x2 = 1:3)
b <- data.frame(x1 = c("A","B","D"), x2 = c("T","F","T"))
a
##   x1 x2
## 1  A  1
## 2  B  2
## 3  C  3
b
##   x1 x2
## 1  A  T
## 2  B  F
## 3  D  T

“Mutating” joins combine variables from the left and right hand sides

ie. full_join(), inner_join(), right_join(), and left_join()

full_join()

full_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2.x x2.y
## 1  A    1    T
## 2  B    2    F
## 3  C    3 <NA>
## 4  D   NA    T

inner_join()

inner_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2.x x2.y
## 1  A    1    T
## 2  B    2    F

left_join()

Join matching rows from b to a

left_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2.x x2.y
## 1  A    1    T
## 2  B    2    F
## 3  C    3 <NA>

right_join()

Join matching rows from a to b

right_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2.x x2.y
## 1  A    1    T
## 2  B    2    F
## 3  D   NA    T

“Filtering” joins keep cases from the left hand side

ie. semi_join() and anti_join()

semi_join()

  • Return all rows in a that have a match in b, keeping only columns from b. Different from inner_join() because it will never duplicate rows of a.
semi_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2
## 1  A  1
## 2  B  2

anti_join()

  • Return all rows from a where there are not matching values in b, keeping just the columns from a
anti_join(a, b, by = "x1")
##   x1 x2
## 1  C  3

Survival data wrangling

dems <- read.csv("dems_dplyr.csv")
dems %>%
  select(Days.to.lastFU, Days.to.death, Days.to.stroke, Days.to.GIB, Days.to.PT) %>%
  replace(is.na(.), Inf) %>%  # which.min cannot handle NA, so we'll make NA's infinity for now
  rowwise() %>% # to allow which.min to search along rows (dplyr naturally looks down columns)
  mutate(
    FUorFEtime = pmin(Days.to.lastFU, Days.to.death, Days.to.stroke,
                      Days.to.GIB, Days.to.PT,
                      na.rm = T),
    FUorFEstatus = which.min(c(Days.to.lastFU, Days.to.death, Days.to.stroke,
                                    Days.to.GIB, Days.to.PT)),
         # numbers correspond to order of the Days* columns
  Event_yn = ifelse(FUorFEstatus == 1, 0, 1)) %>%# condensed variable for survival, 1 if any event
  as.data.frame() %>% # switch back to df so we can see all columns
  head(n=20)

Making functions

  • Problem: dplyr doesn’t know what to do with quotes around the variable name, but you can’t put the column name into a function without quotes because R will try to find it as an object in your environment…

  • Solution: relying on the rlang package (sym, !!, !!!, etc)
    • A good tutorial: http://jonthegeek.com/2018/06/04/writing-custom-tidyverse-functions/
irisSummary <- function(group){
    iris %>%
      group_by(!!sym(group)) %>%
      summarise(mean(Sepal.Length), sd(Sepal.Length))
}

irisSummary(group = "Species")
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   Species    `mean(Sepal.Length)` `sd(Sepal.Length)`
##   <fct>                     <dbl>              <dbl>
## 1 setosa                     5.01              0.352
## 2 versicolor                 5.94              0.516
## 3 virginica                  6.59              0.636
irisScatPlot <- function(x, y){
    iris %>%
    ggplot(aes_string(x, y, col="Species")) +
    geom_point() -> p
  return(p)
}

irisScatPlot(x="Sepal.Length",y="Petal.Length")
